<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/716837-which-would-you-read-first-the">Which would you read first: The Recognitions by William Gaddis, Against the Day by Thomas Pynchon, or Infinite Jest by David Foster Wallace?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_716837'><a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F409.Against_the_Day">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/716837-which-would-you-read-first-the">5 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/716837-which-would-you-read-first-the">See all 5 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/48483884-michael-finocchiaro"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1576692048i/48483884._UX100_CR0,13,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/48483884-michael-finocchiaro">Michael Finocchiaro</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I started with Infinite Jest but it took me a few years to get past the first 100 pages (although it was MORE than worth it once I did). I think that <a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I started with Infinite Jest but it took me a few years to get past the first 100 pages (although it was MORE than worth it once I did). I think that for a long Pynchon book, Mason&amp;Dixon is more pleasurable (once you get past the 18th century diction) than Against the Day which although I loved it has so many Pychonian devices in changing perspective and time travel that a more linear story like M&amp;D would be easier to start with. I have not read The Recognitions and am not sure I will so I can't say...Any reader of Pynchon has to cross Gravity's Rainbow at one time. I read it first and enjoyed it but preferred M&amp;D and AtD to be honest. I also loved Bleeding Edge. <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

